I’ll explain Generational Garbage Collection from absolute zero, step by step, with simple examples.

🧠 First Understand the Real Problem

Imagine your Rails app receives a request.

Inside one request:

params
temp variables
JSON parsing
SQL result objects

👉 Thousands of objects are created.

But after response is sent?

👉 Almost all of them are useless.

They die immediately.

💡 Important Observation (Key Idea)

In real programs:

Most objects live for a very short time.

Example:

def full_name(first, last)
  first + " " + last
end

The " " string, temporary concatenation object, etc.

They live for milliseconds.

They die immediately.

That’s the core idea behind:

“Most objects die young”

🗑️ Now Let’s Think Like Ruby

If Ruby had only one big memory pool:

Every time GC runs, it would:

Scan ALL objects

Check which are alive

Delete dead ones

Even old stable objects like:

Rails config

Loaded classes

Constants

DB connection objects

That’s wasteful.

💥 So Ruby Became Smart

Ruby said:

“If most objects die young, then let’s separate young and old objects.”

🏗️ Ruby Memory Layout (Simplified)

Ruby divides memory into:

1️⃣ Young Generation

Newly created objects go here.

2️⃣ Old Generation

Objects that survive multiple GC cycles go here.

🔄 How It Works (Step-by-Step)

Let’s simulate:

Step 1 – Create objects
a = "hello"
b = "world"

These go into:

👉 Young generation

Step 2 – GC runs

Ruby checks young objects.

If object is unreachable → delete it.

If object is still referenced → it survives.

Step 3 – Surviving Objects

If "hello" still referenced after multiple GCs:

Ruby promotes it to:

👉 Old generation

🎯 Why This Improves Performance

Because:

Most objects die in young generation.

So Ruby mainly scans:

👉 Young generation frequently
👉 Old generation rarely

That saves time.

🧪 Real-World Analogy

Imagine:

School system.

Nursery Class (Young Gen)

Most students leave quickly.

Only few continue.

Senior Class (Old Gen)

Only long-term students remain.

Instead of checking ALL students daily,
principal checks nursery frequently,
senior class occasionally.

Efficient.

⚡ Why This Is Faster?

Without generational GC:

Every GC = scan 1 million objects

With generational GC:

Most GC = scan only 50,000 young objects

Huge performance improvement.

🧠 Important Interview Line

If interviewer asks:

“How does generational GC improve performance?”

You say:

Ruby assumes most objects die young, so it frequently collects the young generation and rarely scans the old generation. This reduces the number of objects checked in each GC cycle and improves performance.

🔥 Now Let’s Make It Even More Clear

Imagine this Rails request:

User.all.map { |u| u.name.upcase }

Temporary objects created:

Enumerator

Blocks

Strings

Array copies

After response?

Dead.

They die in young generation.

Meanwhile:

Rails constants

DB pool

Middleware stack

These survive many cycles → become old generation.

Ruby doesn’t waste time scanning them repeatedly.

🧩 What Happens If Old Object References Young Object?

Ruby keeps track using something called:

Write Barrier

But don’t worry — interviewers usually won’t go that deep unless senior level.

🚀 Final Simple Summary

Generational GC means:

New objects go to young generation

If they survive multiple GC cycles → moved to old generation

Young generation cleaned frequently

Old generation cleaned rarely

This improves speed because most objects die young

